<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WORLD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Soviet poet Yevgeny Yevtushenko says the CIA helped the KGB clamp down on 
Soviet dissidents in 1966 in order to divert world attention from the U.S. 
bombing of Vietnam. In an article in the Soviet weekly Ogonyok, Yevtushenko 
recounts how Sen. Robert F. Kennedy (D-N.Y.) told him that the U.S. 
intelligence service had given its Soviet rival the pseudonyms of dissident 
writers Yuli Daniel and Andrei Sinyavsky. Both were prosecuted with alleged CIA 
evidence. Yevtushenko wrote he learned of the alleged CIA involvement when he 
was invited to the senator's New York headquarters during a visit to the United 
States in November, 1966. 
</P>
